<subSubSection pageId="87" pageNumber="88" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="87" pageNumber="88">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="87" pageNumber="88">
An extremely variable species easily recognised by its deeply divided leaves and white flowers, which are occasionally with dark violet midpetaline bands. The following specimens are outstanding and could each constitute a distinct taxon, but which I hesitate to recognise in the absence of any matching material: 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">Venturi</emphasis>
8624 (BM, K, MO) from Argentina, which has very large leaves 5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5 cm with broad segments, the peduncles up to 6 cm long bearing up to three flowers and is apparently similar to 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus geranioides" order="Solanales" pageId="87" pageNumber="88" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="geranioides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">Convolvulus geranioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Chile; 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">Sandoval &amp; Stark</emphasis>
1025 (K) from Chile, which has small pinnatisect, white-tomentose leaves. There are also densely pubescent specimens from Uruguay (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">Gay</emphasis>
s.n., 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">Seijo et al.</emphasis>
2381, for example) which may accord with 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="subsp. var. var. hirsutus" order="Solanales" pageId="87" pageNumber="88" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="geranioides" subSpecies="var." variety="hirsutus">var. hirsutus</taxonomicName>
Desr. Corolla indumentum and colouring are also outstandingly variable, some corollas completely glabrous while in others the midpetaline bands are pubescent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="87" pageNumber="88">
Two specimens from Bolivia (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">Wood et al.</emphasis>
21956 and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">Bastian</emphasis>
783, both LPB) have finely dissected leaves like 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Desr., Encycl. [Lamarck et al.] 3: 546. 1792. (Desrousseaux" authorityYear="1792" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus laciniatus" order="Solanales" pageId="87" pageNumber="88" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="laciniatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">Convolvulus laciniatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but a hairy apex to the ovary. They probably represent the hybrid between 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Desr., Encycl. [Lamarck et al.] 3: 546. 1792. (Desrousseaux" authorityYear="1792" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus laciniatus" order="Solanales" pageId="87" pageNumber="88" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="laciniatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">Convolvulus laciniatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. R. I. Wood &amp; R. W. Scotland" authorityYear="2015" baseAuthorityName="Wood &amp; Williams &amp; Mitchell &amp; Carine &amp; Harris &amp; Scotland" baseAuthorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus hermanniae subsp. erosus" order="Solanales" pageId="87" pageNumber="88" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="hermanniae" subSpecies="erosus">Convolvulus hermanniae subsp. erosus</taxonomicName>
, certainly 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">Wood</emphasis>
21956 was growing in the vicinity of both parents.
</paragraph>
